docs.abstract: His public art installation in New York’s Madison Square Park takes on the thorny issues roiling American classrooms.
docs.snippet: His public art installation in New York’s Madison Square Park takes on the thorny issues roiling American classrooms.
docs.lead_paragraph: “Just watch your eyes,” the sculptor Hugh Hayden warned as he circumnavigated the wooden school desk he had made from cedar logs, their branches still attached. The limbs erupted from the seat and desktop, in all directions — strange, unruly, alive.

headline.main: Hugh Hayden, Surrealist Sculptor, Addresses the Education Debate
headline.print_headline: Attention Class: Your Desks Are Actually The Lesson

docs.abstract: The Republicans aren’t apologists for Jan. 6 — some chastised President Trump and don’t want him to run again. They just want the country to move on.
docs.snippet: The Republicans aren’t apologists for Jan. 6 — some chastised President Trump and don’t want him to run again. They just want the country to move on.
docs.lead_paragraph: This article is the result of a focus group we held with Republican voters about the events of Jan. 6, 2021, and the health of American democracy. You can also read the article about our Democratic voter focus group on the same issues here. Patrick Healy, the deputy Opinion editor, expands on the takeaways from the focus groups and the intent behind them here in the Opinion Today newsletter.

headline.main: Why Republican Voters Think Americans Have to Get Over Jan. 6
headline.print_headline: ‘Things Happen in Life. Quit Being a Wuss.’
